FIVE people, including an infant, died in a horrific accident on the R66 near Eshowe, KZN. The victims were in a taxi that collided with a Ford Ranger in the late afternoon on Tuesday, 7 June. All five – two women, two men and an infant – were killed instantly on impact while other passengers sustained injuries ranging from critical to serious. Transport MEC Peggy Nkonyeni was saddened that in less than a month, the province had to experience yet another horrific accident claiming yet so many lives. According to a report received by the department, at around 5.30pm, a minibus taxi collided with a Ford Ranger, instantly killing five occupants in the taxi. Four people sustained critical to serious injuries, and were rushed to hospital. Nkonyeni sent her condolences to the victims’ families, calling on motorists to always be extra cautious. “This is really saddening, especially as we are still recovering from another gruesome accident that claimed the lives of 16 people on the N3 almost two weeks ago. My heartfelt condolences to the families of all victims. I also wish those who sustained injuries a speedily recovery.” She further directed law enforcement to conduct a thorough investigation to determine the cause of the accident.